{
  "answer": "To show that the AR(1) model $ y_t = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 y_{t-1} + u_t $ is dynamically complete under the assumption $ \\mathrm{E}(u_t | y_{t-1}, y_{t-2}, \\dots) = 0 $, follow these steps:\\nStep 1: Recall the definition of dynamic completeness. A model is dynamically complete if all relevant past information is captured in the conditional expectation $ \\mathrm{E}(y_t | y_{t-1}, y_{t-2}, \\dots) $. This means that the error term $ u_t $ contains no predictable components based on past values of $ y $.\\nStep 2: Use the given assumption $ \\mathrm{E}(u_t | y_{t-1}, y_{t-2}, \\dots) = 0 $. This implies that the error term $ u_t $ is orthogonal to all past values of $ y $, meaning there is no serial correlation between $ u_t $ and any lagged values of $ y $.\\nStep 3: Substitute the AR(1) model into the conditional expectation. Since $ y_t = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 y_{t-1} + u_t $, the conditional expectation becomes $ \\mathrm{E}(y_t | y_{t-1}, y_{t-2}, \\dots) = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 y_{t-1} + \\mathrm{E}(u_t | y_{t-1}, y_{t-2}, \\dots) $.\\nStep 4: Apply the assumption $ \\mathrm{E}(u_t | y_{t-1}, y_{t-2}, \\dots) = 0 $. This simplifies the conditional expectation to $ \\mathrm{E}(y_t | y_{t-1}, y_{t-2}, \\dots) = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 y_{t-1} $.\\nStep 5: Conclude that the AR(1) model is dynamically complete because all relevant past information ($ y_{t-1} $) is fully captured in the conditional expectation, and the error term $ u_t $ contains no additional predictable components."
