  "answer": "Step 1: Start with the definition of the natural logarithm function and its derivative.\\nThe derivative of the natural logarithm function is given as $ \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{1}{x} $. This means that for a small change $ \\Delta x $ around a point $ x_0 $, the corresponding change in $ y = \\log(x) $ can be approximated using the derivative:\\\\\\n$$ \\Delta y \\approx \\frac{1}{x_0} \\Delta x $$\\\\\\nThis is derived directly from the definition of the derivative in calculus.\\\\\\nStep 2: Rewrite the change in $ y $ in terms of the logarithmic difference.\\nSince $ y = \\log(x) $, the change in $ y $ can also be expressed as the difference of logarithms:\\\\\\n$$ \\Delta y = \\log(x_1) - \\log(x_0) $$\\\\\\nUsing the property of logarithms, $ \\log(a) - \\log(b) = \\log(a/b) $, this becomes:\\\\\\n$$ \\Delta y = \\log\\left(\\frac{x_1}{x_0}\\right) $$\\\\\\nStep 3: Approximate the logarithmic difference for small changes.\\nFor small changes in $ x $, the argument of the logarithm $ \\frac{x_1}{x_0} $ is close to 1. Using the approximation $ \\log(1 + z) \\approx z $ for small $ z $, we can write:\\\\\\n$$ \\log\\left(\\frac{x_1}{x_0}\\right) \\approx \\frac{x_1 - x_0}{x_0} $$\\\\\\nStep 4: Combine the results.\\nSubstituting back into the expression for $ \\Delta y $, we get:\\\\\\n$$ \\log(x_1) - \\log(x_0) \\approx \\frac{x_1 - x_0}{x_0} $$\\\\\\nThus, the approximation $ \\log(x_1) - \\log(x_0) \\approx (x_1 - x_0)/x_0 $ is derived using calculus principles."
