{
  "answer": "To derive the marginal rate of substitution (MRS) formula from the definition provided in the text, follow these steps:\\nStep 1: Understand the concept of MRS. MRS represents the rate at which a consumer is willing to substitute one good for another while maintaining the same level of utility (i.e., staying on the same indifference curve). This reflects the trade-off between two goods.\\nStep 2: Recall the definition of an indifference curve. An indifference curve shows all combinations of two goods that yield the same level of satisfaction or utility to the consumer.\\nStep 3: Relate MRS to the slope of the indifference curve. The slope of the indifference curve at any point is the rate of change of the two goods along the curve. Mathematically, this slope is represented as the negative ratio of the marginal utilities of the two goods.\\nStep 4: Express MRS mathematically. Let U(x, y) represent the utility function where x and y are the quantities of two goods. Then, the MRS is given by:\\\\\\ MRS = -MUx / MUy \\\\\\ where MUx is the marginal utility of good x and MUy is the marginal utility of good y.\\nStep 5: Interpret the relationship. Since the slope of the indifference curve measures the rate at which the consumer is willing to substitute one good for another, MRS directly corresponds to this slope. Thus, MRS provides a precise measure of the trade-off between the two goods along the indifference curve."
