  "answer": "Step 1: Expected Value of a Bernoulli Random Variable \\\\\\nGiven the probability mass function (PMF) of a Bernoulli random variable X:\\\\\\\\[ P(X=0) = 1-p \\] \\\\\\[ P(X=1) = p \\] \\\\\\nThe expected value E(X) is calculated as follows: \\\\\\[ E(X) = \\\\[1 \\\\times P(X=1) + 0 \\\\times P(X=0)\\] \\\\\\[ E(X) = 1 \\\\times p + 0 \\\\times (1-p) \\\\\\[ E(X) = p \\\\\\nThus, the expected value of a Bernoulli random variable is simply the success probability p. \\\\\\nStep 2: Variance of a Bernoulli Random Variable \\\\\\nThe variance of a random variable is defined as: \\\\\\[ \\\\[var(X) = E(X^2) - [E(X)]^2\\] \\\\\\nFor a Bernoulli random variable, since X can only take values 0 or 1: \\\\\\[ E(X^2) = 1^2 \\\\times P(X=1) + 0^2 \\\\times P(X=0) \\\\\\[ E(X^2) = 1 \\\\times p + 0 \\\\times (1-p) \\\\\\[ E(X^2) = p \\\\\\nSubstituting into the formula for variance: \\\\\\[ var(X) = E(X^2) - [E(X)]^2 \\\\\\[ var(X) = p - p^2 \\\\\\[ var(X) = p(1-p) \\\\\\[ var(X) = pq \\\\\\nWhere q = 1-p. Thus, the variance of a Bernoulli random variable is given by pq, where p is the success probability and q is the failure probability."
}

