  "answer": "Step 1: Recall the definition of the Hansen-Sargan test statistic. It is defined as the minimized value of the GMM criterion function, denoted as $ Q(\\hat{\\\\pmb{\\\\[heta]}}, \\\\[hmb{y}}) $. This statistic measures the discrepancy between the sample moments and the model-implied moments under the null hypothesis of valid overidentifying restrictions.\\nStep 2: Under the null hypothesis, the first-order conditions for minimizing the GMM criterion function yield the equation $ F^{\\[top]}(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]}) \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi} P\\[A} \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} \\\\[hmb{f}(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]}) = \\\\[mathbf{0} $. Using this, we derive the asymptotic distribution of $ n^{1/2}(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]} - \\\\[hmb{\\[heta]}_0) $, which is proportional to $ -\\\\[left( \\\\[frac{1}{n} F_0^{\\[top]} \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi} P\\[A} \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} F_0 \\\\[right)]^{-1} n^{-1/2} F_0^{\\[top]} \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi} P\\[A} \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} f_0 $.\\nStep 3: Perform a Taylor expansion around the true parameter $ \\\\[hmb{\\[heta]}_0 $. This leads to the approximation $ P_A \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} f(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]}) \\\\[approx] P_A \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} f_0 + n^{-1/2} P_A \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} F_0 n^{1/2} (\\\\[hata{\\[heta]} - \\\\[hmb{\\[heta]}_0) $. Substituting the expression for $ n^{1/2}(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]} - \\\\[hmb{\\[heta]}_0) $, we simplify to $ \\\\[big(\\[mathbf{I} - P_{P_A \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} F_0} \\\\[big)} P_A \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} f_0 $.\\nStep 4: Substitute this result into the expression for $ Q(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]}, \\\\[hmb{y}}) $. After simplification, we find that $ Q(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]}, \\\\[hmb{y}}) $ is asymptotically equivalent to $ f_0^{\\[top]} \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi} \\\\[big(P_A - P_{P_A \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} F_0} \\\\[big)} \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} f_0 $.\\nStep 5: Recognize that the difference of projection matrices $ P_A - P_{P_A \\\\[hmb{\\varPsi}^{\\[top]} F_0} $ is itself an orthogonal projection matrix with rank $ l - k $, where $ l $ is the number of moment conditions and $ k $ is the number of parameters.\\nStep 6: Conclude that under the null hypothesis, $ Q(\\\\[hata{\\[heta]}, \\\\[hmb{y}}) $ is asymptotically distributed as $ \\\\[chi]^2(l - k) $. This result aligns with the standard chi-squared distribution for overidentification tests in GMM estimation."
