{
  "answer": "To prove that a linear functional $\\phi$ on a normed vector space $S$ is continuous if and only if it is bounded:\\nStep 1: Assume $\\phi$ is continuous. By definition of continuity at $0 \\in S$, for every $\\epsilon > 0$, there exists $\\delta > 0$ such that $\\|x\\|_s < \\delta$ implies $|\\phi(x)| < \\epsilon$. Choose $\\epsilon = 1$, then there exists $\\delta > 0$ such that $|\\phi(x)| < 1$ whenever $\\|x\\|_s < \\delta$. For any nonzero $x \\in S$, let $y = \\frac{\\delta}{2\\|x\\|_s}x$. Then $\\|y\\|_s = \\frac{\\delta}{2} < \\delta$, so $|\\phi(y)| < 1$. Substituting $y = \\frac{\\delta}{2\\|x\\|_s}x$, we get $|\\phi(x)| < \\frac{2}{\\delta}\\|x\\|_s$. Hence, $\\phi$ is bounded.\\nStep 2: Assume $\\phi$ is bounded. Then there exists $M > 0$ such that $|\\phi(x)| \\leq M\\|x\\|_s$ for all $x \\in S$. To show continuity, fix $\\epsilon > 0$. Let $\\delta = \\frac{\\epsilon}{M}$. If $\\|x - y\\|_s < \\delta$, then $|\\phi(x) - \\phi(y)| = |\\phi(x - y)| \\leq M\\|x - y\\|_s < M\\delta = \\epsilon$. Thus, $\\phi$ is continuous.\\nTherefore, a linear functional $\\phi$ on a normed vector space $S$ is continuous if and only if it is bounded."
}

