{
  "answer": "To derive the F-statistic for testing the restriction \\(\\beta_2 + \\beta_3 = 1\\) in the Cobb-Douglas production function, expressed in terms of RSS and \\(R^2\\):\\nStep 1: Recall the general formula for the F-statistic in terms of \\(R^2\\): \\\\[ F = \\frac{(R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^2 - R_{\\mathrm{R}}^2)/m}{(1 - R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^2)/(n-k)} \\\\]\", where \\(R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^2\\) and \\(R_{\\mathrm{R}}^2\\) are the \\(R^2\\) values from the unrestricted and restricted regressions, respectively. Here, \\(m\\) is the number of restrictions, and \\(n-k\\) represents the degrees of freedom for the unrestricted model.\\nStep 2: Relate \\(R^2\\) to RSS (Residual Sum of Squares). For both the unrestricted and restricted models, we know that: \\\\[ R^2 = 1 - \\frac{\\text{RSS}}{\\text{TSS}}, \\\\]\\] where TSS is the total sum of squares.\\nStep 3: Express the difference in \\(R^2\\) values: \\\\[ R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^2 - R_{\\mathrm{R}}^2 = \\left(1 - \\frac{\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{UR}}}{\\text{TSS}}\\right) - \\left(1 - \\frac{\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{R}}}{\\text{TSS}}\\right) = \\frac{\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{R}} - \\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{UR}}}{\\text{TSS}}. \\\\]\", where \\(\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{UR}}\\) and \\(\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{R}}\\) are the residual sums of squares for the unrestricted and restricted models, respectively.\\nStep 4: Substitute this into the F-statistic formula: \\\\[ F = \\frac{\\left(\\frac{\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{R}} - \\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{UR}}}{\\text{TSS}}\\right)/m}{\\left(1 - R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^2\\right)/(n-k)}. \\\\]\", which simplifies to: \\\\[ F = \\frac{(\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{R}} - \\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{UR}})/m}{\\text{RSS}_{\\mathrm{UR}}/(n-k)}. \\\\]\", completing the derivation."
}

