{
  "answer": "To derive the log-likelihood function for the full maximum likelihood estimation of the Tobit model with endogenous explanatory variables, we proceed as follows:\\nStep 1: Start with the joint distribution of \\((y_1, y_2)\\) given \\(\\mathbf{z}\\): \\\\[ f(y_1, y_2 \\mid \\mathbf{z}) = f(y_1 \\mid y_2, \\mathbf{z}) f(y_2 \\mid \\mathbf{z}) \\\\. \\\\ This decomposition mirrors the approach used in the probit case.\\nStep 2: Express the conditional distributions. Since \\(y_2\\) is determined by the reduced form equation \\(y_2 = \\mathbf{z}_1 \\delta_{21} + \\mathbf{z}_2 \\delta_{22} + v_2\\), its distribution given \\(\\mathbf{z}\\) is normal with mean \\(\\mathbf{z} \\delta_2\\) and variance \\(\\sigma_{v_2}^2\\). Thus, \\\\[ f(y_2 \\mid \\mathbf{z}) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi \\sigma_{v_2}^2}} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{(y_2 - \\mathbf{z} \\delta_2)^2}{2\\sigma_{v_2}^2}\\right) \\\\. \\\\ \\\\\\nStep 3: For \\(y_1\\), note that it depends on \\(y_2\\) through the latent variable formulation. Specifically, the latent variable is \\(y_1^* = \\mathbf{z}_1 \\delta_1 + \\alpha_1 y_2 + u_1\\), and the observed \\(y_1\\) is defined as \\(y_1 = \\max(0, y_1^*)\\). The conditional density \\(f(y_1 \\mid y_2, \\mathbf{z})\\) accounts for both the censored and uncensored cases. For uncensored observations (where \\(y_1 > 0\\)), the density is normal with mean \\(\\mathbf{z}_1 \\delta_1 + \\alpha_1 y_2\\) and variance \\(\\sigma_{u_1}^2\\). For censored observations (where \\(y_1 = 0\\)), the probability of being censored is given by the cumulative normal distribution evaluated at zero.\\nStep 4: Combine the components into the joint density. The full likelihood function is the product of the densities for all observations, taking into account whether each observation is censored or not. Let \\(I_i\\) denote an indicator for whether observation \\(i\\) is censored (\\(I_i = 1\\)) or uncensored (\\(I_i = 0\\)). Then, the joint density for observation \\(i\\) is: \\\\[ f(y_{1i}, y_{2i} \\mid \\mathbf{z}_i) = I_i \\Phi\\left(-\\frac{\\mathbf{z}_{1i} \\delta_1 + \\alpha_1 y_{2i}}{\\sigma_{u_1}}\\right) + (1 - I_i) \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi \\sigma_{u_1}^2}} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{(y_{1i} - \\mathbf{z}_{1i} \\delta_1 - \\alpha_1 y_{2i})^2}{2\\sigma_{u_1}^2}\\right) \\times \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2\\pi \\sigma_{v_2}^2}} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{(y_{2i} - \\mathbf{z}_i \\delta_2)^2}{2\\sigma_{v_2}^2}\\right) \\\\. \\\\ \\\\\\nStep 5: Take the logarithm to obtain the log-likelihood function. The log-likelihood is the sum over all observations of the logarithm of the joint density: \\\\[ \\ln L(\\delta_1, \\alpha_1, \\delta_2, \\sigma_{u_1}, \\sigma_{v_2}) = \\sum_{i=1}^N \\left[ I_i \\ln \\Phi\\left(-\\frac{\\mathbf{z}_{1i} \\delta_1 + \\alpha_1 y_{2i}}{\\sigma_{u_1}}\\right) + (1 - I_i) \\left( -\\frac{1}{2} \\ln(2\\pi) - \\ln(\\sigma_{u_1}) - \\frac{(y_{1i} - \\mathbf{z}_{1i} \\delta_1 - \\alpha_1 y_{2i})^2}{2\\sigma_{u_1}^2} - \\frac{1}{2} \\ln(2\\pi) - \\ln(\\sigma_{v_2}) - \\frac{(y_{2i} - \\mathbf{z}_i \\delta_2)^2}{2\\sigma_{v_2}^2} \\right) \\right] \\\\. \\\\ \\\\\\nThus, the log-likelihood function is derived by combining the contributions from the censored and uncensored cases, incorporating the normal densities for both \\(y_1\\) and \\(y_2\\)."
}

