{
  "answer": "To prove that if $ |\\alpha| < 1 $, then $ \\alpha^n \\to 0 $:\\nStep 1: Recall the definition of convergence. A sequence $ \\alpha^n $ converges to 0 if, for every $ \\epsilon > 0 $, there exists an integer $ N $ such that for all $ n > N $, we have $ |\\alpha^n - 0| < \\epsilon $.\\nStep 2: Since $ |\\alpha| < 1 $, we know that $ |\\alpha|^n $ decreases as $ n $ increases because raising a number less than 1 to higher powers makes it smaller.\\nStep 3: Let $ \\epsilon > 0 $ be arbitrary. We need to find $ N $ such that $ |\\alpha|^n < \\epsilon $ for all $ n > N $.\\nStep 4: Take the natural logarithm of both sides of $ |\\alpha|^n < \\epsilon $. This gives $ n \\ln(|\\alpha|) < \\ln(\\epsilon) $.\\nStep 5: Since $ |\\alpha| < 1 $, $ \\ln(|\\alpha|) < 0 $. Dividing through by $ \\ln(|\\alpha|) $ reverses the inequality, yielding $ n > \\frac{\\ln(\\epsilon)}{\\ln(|\\alpha|)} $.\\nStep 6: Choose $ N $ to be any integer greater than $ \\frac{\\ln(\\epsilon)}{\\ln(|\\alpha|)} $. Then for all $ n > N $, $ |\\alpha|^n < \\epsilon $, proving that $ \\alpha^n \\to 0 $."
