{
  "answer": "To derive the conditions under which a stochastic choice function is rationalizable, we follow these steps:\\nStep 1: Understand the concept of rationalizability. A stochastic choice function is rationalizable if it can be represented as a probability distribution over deterministic choice functions derived from some underlying preference relation.\\nStep 2: Establish the necessary properties of the preference relation. From the provided context, the preference relation > must satisfy transitivity and completeness. Transitivity ensures that if x > y and y > z, then x > z. Completeness ensures that for any two alternatives x and y, either x > y, y > x, or x ~ y (indifference).\\nStep 3: Represent preferences with a utility function. As shown in 1.B.3, if a utility function u(Â·) represents the preference relation >, then x > y if and only if u(x) â¥ u(y). Furthermore, if u(Â·) is strictly increasing, another utility function v(Â·) can represent the same preferences if v(x) â¥ v(y) whenever u(x) â¥ u(y).\\nStep 4: Apply the Weak Axiom of Revealed Preference (WARP). WARP, as implied in the context, ensures that if an alternative x is chosen when available, and y is chosen when both x and y are available, then y cannot be chosen when only x is available. This axiom helps ensure that the stochastic choice function aligns with a rational preference structure.\\nStep 5: Conclude the conditions. The stochastic choice function is rationalizable if it satisfies WARP and can be represented by a probability distribution over deterministic choice functions derived from a preference relation that is complete and transitive.\\nThus, the conditions are: (i) Transitivity and completeness of preferences, (ii) Representation of preferences by a utility function, and (iii) Satisfaction of WARP."
