{
  "answer": "To derive the optimal bid function for a second-price auction with $ N $ bidders and uniform valuations on $ [\\underline{\\tau}, \\overline{\\tau}] $:\\nStep 1: Understand the structure of the second-price auction.\\nIn a second-price auction, the highest bidder wins but pays the second-highest bid. Each bidder maximizes their expected utility by bidding truthfully, i.e., bidding their true valuation $ \\tau_h $, because bidding higher than $ \\tau_h $ risks overpaying, while bidding lower reduces the chance of winning without gaining any advantage.\\nStep 2: Analyze the probability of winning.\\nFor agent $ h $, the probability of winning the auction when bidding $ p $ is given as $ \\left[\\frac{\\varphi(p) - \\underline{\\tau}}{\\overline{\\tau} - \\underline{\\tau}}\\right]^{N-1} $, where $ \\varphi(\\cdot) $ is the inverse of the bid function $ \\beta(\\cdot) $. This reflects the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the other $ N-1 $ bidders' valuations.\\nStep 3: Determine the expected payment.\\nSince the winner pays the second-highest bid, the expected payment is based on the second-highest valuation among the $ N-1 $ other bidders. For uniform valuations, the expected second-highest valuation is proportional to the range of valuations.\\nStep 4: Derive the optimal bid function.\\nIn a second-price auction, the optimal strategy is to bid truthfully. Thus, the optimal bid function is $ \\beta(\\tau) = \\tau $, as each bidder should bid their true valuation to maximize their expected utility.\\nTherefore, the optimal bid function for a second-price auction is $ \\boxed{\\beta(\\tau) = \\tau} $."
}

