{
  "answer": "Step 1: Recall that the incremental F-test compares two nested models: one with the original variables (old model) and another with the original variables plus the new variable (new model). The F-statistic is defined as:\\nF = [(ESS_new - ESS_old) / k] / [RSS_new / (n - p_new)]\\nwhere k is the number of new regressors added, n is the sample size, and p_new is the total number of parameters in the new model.\\nStep 2: The t-test for the new variable tests whether its coefficient is significantly different from zero. Its square equals the F-statistic when the new variable is the only one being tested in the F-test.\\nStep 3: For the F-test and t-test to yield identical results, the following conditions must hold:\\nCondition 1: The new variable must be the only variable in the F-test.\\nCondition 2: The degrees of freedom adjustment in the F-test must match the degrees of freedom in the t-test.\\nProof:\\nLet Î²_3 denote the coefficient of the new variable X_3. In the t-test, the null hypothesis is H0: Î²_3 = 0. The t-statistic is calculated as t = Î²_3 / SE(Î²_3), where SE(Î²_3) is the standard error of Î²_3.\\nIn the F-test, the numerator simplifies to [(ESS_new - ESS_old) / k], which becomes (ESS_new - ESS_old) since k = 1. The denominator is RSS_new / (n - p_new).\\nStep 4: When testing only one variable (X_3), the numerator of the F-statistic becomes equivalent to the square of the t-statistic because:\\nESS_new - ESS_old = Î²_3^2 * Var(X_3 | X_2)\\nand SE(Î²_3)^2 = Var(X_3 | X_2) / [Var(X_3 | X_2) + Ï^2], where Ï^2 is the residual variance.\\nThus, F = t^2 when the new variable is the only one being tested, and the degrees of freedom adjustments align.\\nConclusion: The incremental F-test and t-test yield identical results when the new variable is the sole variable being tested in the F-test, and the degrees of freedom adjustments are consistent."
