{
  "answer": "Step 1: Define the mathematical relationship between MC and ATC.\\\\\\nLet ATC(q) = TC(q)/q, where TC(q) is the total cost function and q is the quantity of output. Then, the marginal cost (MC) is the derivative of the total cost with respect to quantity, i.e., MC(q) = dTC(q)/dq. Using the quotient rule, the derivative of ATC(q) with respect to q is:\\\\\\n(dATC(q)/dq) = [(q * dTC(q)/dq - TC(q)) / q^2] = [(q * MC(q) - TC(q)) / q^2].\\\\\\\\nStep 2: Analyze when ATC is falling or rising.\\\\\\nWhen MC < ATC, the numerator (q * MC(q) - TC(q)) is negative, meaning dATC(q)/dq < 0, so ATC is falling. When MC > ATC, the numerator is positive, meaning dATC(q)/dq > 0, so ATC is rising. At the point where MC = ATC, the numerator equals zero, meaning dATC(q)/dq = 0, which corresponds to the minimum point of the ATC curve.\\\\\\\\nStep 3: Explain why MC intersects ATC at its minimum point.\\\\\\nThe intersection occurs because MC represents the incremental cost of producing one more unit, while ATC reflects the average cost per unit. As long as MC is below ATC, adding one more unit lowers the average cost. Once MC exceeds ATC, adding another unit raises the average cost. Therefore, the point where MC equals ATC is the exact point where ATC stops decreasing and starts increasing, marking its minimum."
}

